name: Beckenbauer '74 - Print
description:
'Der Kaiser' has had a career that any player would be envious of. A career which saw him play over 400 times for his home town club of Bayern Munich as well as receiving 103 caps for the German national team. Eight years after his first World Cup final appearance, he would make a return to centre stage where he captained his side to a 2-1 victory over Cruyff's Dutch team.

He is often recognised as the original 'Libero', in an era where defenders were seen as stoppers, he revolutionised the way in which a sweeper could play the beautiful game and for that we are eternally grateful.

name: Cruyff '74 - Print
description:
Widely regarded as the greatest European player of all time, Johan Cruyff was capable of creating magic on the pitch. Part of the famous 1970s Ajax squad which won three consecutive European Cups with 'Total Football' being at the core of their success. 

With fellow Ajax team mates Haan, Keizer, Krol, Neeskens, Rep and Suurbier, Cruyff helped carry across this revolutionary tactic to the Dutch national team for the 1974 World Cup in Germany.

Cruyff was instrumental in Netherlands' journey to the final, scoring 3 goals along the way. Unfortunately after an early lead in the final, they weren't able to defeat tournaments hosts West Germany however the 1974 World Cup is still regarded as Netherlands and Cruyff's tournament.

name: Rossi '82 - Print
description:
Paolo Rossi is something of an enigma. In a relatively short playing career which saw him only play over 250 games, he has managed to go down as an Italian hero. 

44 years after their last World Cup triumph in France, the 1982 World Cup was a return to success for the Azzurri and Rossi was the catalyst behind their famous 3-1 victory over West Germany in the final.

He is one of only two players to win a World Cup, win the Golden Ball and to finish as top goalscorer in a single World Cup. Later that year he was named European Footballer of the Year and World Player of the Year. 1982 will be a year that Rossi will never forget.

name: Maradona '86 - Print
description:
Diego Armando Maradona stood only 5"5 but the impact that he made on the football world is unmeasurable. Making his professional debut aged only 15, he would go on to have a playing career which lasted 21 years. Wearing the famous number 10 for great clubs such as Boca Juniors, Barcelona and Napoli but it is whilst wearing the number 10 for the Argentine national team, where his greatest achievements lie.

Narrowly missing out in the 1978 winning squad, he first made his World Cup appearance at Spain '82. Being grouped with Brazil and eventual winners, it meant that the second round was as far as they would go. However in 1986, it was Argentinas and Maradona's turn to shine. In a competition where two of the World Cups most famous ever moments would occur with Maradona being at the centre of both. Diego Maradona would help Argentina to defeat Bulgaria, Uruguay, England and West Germany to win their 2nd World Cup.
